1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:16,720
I was talking to a friend of mine and I was really frustrated.

2
00:00:16,720 --> 00:00:24,000
I told my friend, even if your goal was to be president of the United States, your plan

3
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:29,000
for that goal would still just need to be a single page.

4
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:35,000
I'm not a political scientist and I was not trying to convince my friend to run for president.

5
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:42,000
But I was arguing to my friend that more people would be able to achieve their really big goals.

6
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:48,000
If they knew how to design a plan for that goal, that was just a single page.

7
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:54,000
If their goals were really big, like, write a book or climb a mountain or start a YouTube channel.

8
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Be president of the United States, even if their goals were really big, they would still just need to be a single page.

9
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:04,000
And my friend looked at me kind of like, you're looking at me now.

10
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:06,000
Like, what do you mean, just a single page?

11
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:08,000
So let me explain.

12
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:13,000
My name is Dr. Sarah Glova and for years, I was a business reporter and podcast host.

13
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:21,000
Meaning, I spent my days interviewing people about how they achieved their really big goals.

14
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:28,000
I interviewed people who started companies, started movements, invented new technology.

15
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:30,000
I interviewed a lot of firsts.

16
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:37,000
So like the first woman or the first person of color to break a record or hit a certain level of leadership in their industry.

17
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:42,000
And in all these interviews, even though all the people were really different,

18
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:45,000
I started to notice a pattern.

19
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:52,000
Even though all the people were really different, there were certain things that everybody seemed to be doing as they worked on their goal.

20
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:58,000
There was a pattern to how they set, worked on, and achieved their really big goal.

21
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:01,000
And I nerd it out on this for a couple years.

22
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:06,000
I looked to see if the research could verify what I was seeing in this pattern.

23
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:14,000
And then I tested it with a number of folks and I found that there was a way to execute this pattern for any goal.

24
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:19,000
And it worked best if you kept it to just a single page.

25
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:25,000
Now what I would really like to do at this point is go back in time and give this to young Sarah.

26
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:32,000
Because young Sarah really could have used help getting clear on her goals, figuring out how to work on those goals.

27
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:39,000
But I don't have a time machine. So instead of going back and sharing it with young Sarah, I would love if you want to check it out to share it with you.

28
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:40,000
Sound good?

29
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:43,000
Alright, so let's look at this plan for a goal.

30
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:45,000
I mentioned it has to be a single page.

31
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:47,000
And normally I would say go grab a sheet of paper.

32
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:50,000
But if you're listening to this and you can't go grab a sheet paper, that's fine.

33
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:52,000
The plan is actually so simple.

34
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:55,000
You can even just imagine a sheet of paper.

35
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:01,000
So imagine a space about the size of a single sheet of paper.

36
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:06,000
Now the first thing we're going to do since we're working on our goal is on our single sheet of paper.

37
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:10,000
We're going to write down our specific goal.

38
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:13,000
Did y'all hear me say that word specific?

39
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:18,000
It's going to get so specific that you couldn't trade paper with anybody else.

40
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:20,000
This is your page.

41
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:23,000
So if your goal is to write a book, guess what?

42
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:25,000
There's a lot of other people out there who want to write a book.

43
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:30,000
But how can you get so specific as you described this goal so that it's just yours?

44
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:32,000
Nobody else could take your sheet of paper.

45
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:36,000
Some of the things when I interview folks about big goals that they've achieved,

46
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:41,000
some of the things that they get clear about really early on are things like,

47
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:44,000
what is my goal and why do I want to achieve it?

48
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:46,000
What does this goal mean to me?

49
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:52,000
What are the strengths that I have that I can put into play for this goal?

50
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:56,000
The unique strengths that are unique to me that will work for this goal.

51
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:58,000
When do I want to do this thing by?

52
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:00,000
And what is working on it look like?

53
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:03,000
Is this like a nights and weekends thing, or are we doing it every day?

54
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:07,000
So you want to get really specific until this goal is just yours.

55
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:09,000
And it doesn't take out much space.

56
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:13,000
Just the first, like, third of your single sheet of paper you're going to interview yourself

57
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:15,000
around this goal.

58
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:17,000
After this, we're going to work on our goal.

59
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:20,000
That's the easy part, right?

60
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:24,000
I noticed a lot of people getting stuck in this phase as I test it out this plan.

61
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:31,000
And so something we do together is we talk about how to work on our goal and not around our goal.

62
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:34,000
I have a story for this one that I think many of you are going to recognize.

63
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:38,000
I want you to think about that friend of yours, that person you know,

64
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:43,000
who hates their job, and they swear they're going to get a new one, right?

65
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:46,000
But every time you talk to them, you're like, hey, how's the job hunt going?

66
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:49,000
They're like, oh, I'm tweaking my resume right now.

67
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:51,000
Gotta get that resume right.

68
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:54,000
You see in a couple of weeks later, and you're like, hey, do you apply anywhere?

69
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:57,000
And they're like, actually, I'm getting new headshots this week.

70
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:01,000
So I'm going to be updating that LinkedIn profile this weekend.

71
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:08,000
Every time you talk to them, it's like they're spending their time setting those dominoes up just right.

72
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:10,000
They're in that planning phase.

73
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:12,000
Because that planning phase is safe.

74
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:13,000
We're getting things done.

75
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:14,000
We're being productive.

76
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:18,000
But are we putting ourselves out there for those really big actions?

77
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:24,000
So in the middle of your page, something you can do is write down a couple dates, a couple deadlines.

78
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:28,000
And then underneath those dates and deadlines, you're going to put a couple milestones,

79
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:31,000
a couple key tasks that you're going to work on.

80
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:35,000
And these are going to be big things, things that move the needle.

81
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:39,000
Because let me tell you all, those people that I interviewed who accomplished really big things,

82
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:42,000
they actually had just as many things on there to do lists as we do.

83
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:47,000
But they were really good at identifying the priority actions.

84
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:51,000
So with all the noise, all the things that they could do in front of them,

85
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:57,000
they were able to pick out the most important things and to move those things forward.

86
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:02,000
So in the middle of your paper, you're just going to have date, a couple milestones, date,

87
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:06,000
a couple milestones, like three or four times down on your sheet of paper.

88
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:11,000
And what you're going to focus on when you're writing those things are those key priority actions.

89
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:16,000
The stuff that even feels a little risky, putting yourself out there,

90
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:20,000
doing those job applications, writing that book draft,

91
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:23,000
focusing on those key things that will move the needle forward.

92
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:25,000
And I know it's scary.

93
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:28,000
I wish I could tell you that you won't fall down,

94
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:32,000
but I got to tell you based on the interviews I did, a lot of us fall down.

95
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:37,000
But you know what's so great is if you do that key priority action and you do fall down,

96
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:39,000
you're going to learn from it.

97
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:43,000
And when you learn from it and pick yourself up and keep moving,

98
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:47,000
you're going to get further ahead than if you had just been in that domino space.

99
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:50,000
So the people that I interviewed were really good at this,

100
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:55,000
figuring out how to take those priority actions and keep moving.

101
00:06:55,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Now, we've done two sections of our single page and we only have one left.

102
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:03,000
But I have to ask you a question at this point.

103
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:08,000
I want you to imagine that you're working on this big goal and you get stuck.

104
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:15,000
So you get to a place where you have a question or you need to get some inspiration

105
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:17,000
from somebody to keep moving.

106
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:20,000
I want to ask you who you would call.

107
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:26,000
So do you have somebody in your life like a parent or a colleague or a family friend

108
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:29,000
or somebody used to go to school with that guy who lives down the street

109
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:32,000
who has worked on a similar thing to what you're working on?

110
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:35,000
Do you have somebody you could call?

111
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:39,000
I want you to think for a second about what we've written so far on your page,

112
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:41,000
your specific goal of the priorities you're setting.

113
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:44,000
If you had a question about something that was there,

114
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:47,000
do you have somebody who would pick up the phone?

115
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:51,000
So quick show of hands, how many of you thought of somebody?

116
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:54,000
Okay, that right there that we just saw,

117
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:57,000
that's the third piece of our single page plan.

118
00:07:57,000 --> 00:07:59,000
It's community.

119
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:03,000
It's the people who you would call if you've got stuck.

120
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:06,000
And based on the interviews that I've done, it's not if you get stuck.

121
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:07,000
It's when you get stuck.

122
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:09,000
Because when you're working on something really big,

123
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:12,000
when you're here and you're trying to get there,

124
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:15,000
when you want something that you haven't had before,

125
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:17,000
you're gonna get stuck.

126
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:22,000
And so it's really important for us to think about the people who can help and support us.

127
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:25,000
Honestly, it's my favorite part of every interview that I do.

128
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:30,000
It's when the people that I interview talk to me about the coaches or mentors

129
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:32,000
who are there for them.

130
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:35,000
When they stumbled, when they had a question,

131
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:38,000
it comes up in every interview, even if I don't ask about it.

132
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:42,000
That's how crucial the community pieces.

133
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:45,000
So I want you to think about who you would call when you pick up,

134
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:47,000
oh, I did the elder millennial phone, didn't I?

135
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:50,000
I want you to think about who you would call when you pick up the phone.

136
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:51,000
There we go.

137
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:56,000
And what you're gonna do on your single page is you're gonna start writing down some names that come to mind.

138
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:00,000
So that you can bring your community to the forefront for yourself.

139
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:05,000
You can remember who's supporting you, but there's something else crucial we want to do here.

140
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:09,000
Because I want to remind you, when you're working on something that you haven't done before,

141
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:16,000
you're gonna get to a point where you have to cross a gap that's new territory for you.

142
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:21,000
I guarantee you there's somebody out there who's been through that kind of territory before.

143
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:24,000
But they might not be in your network yet.

144
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:26,000
And that's what's really key.

145
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Here in this part of the plan, we want to think about the kind of challenges that we might encounter,

146
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:32,000
or the challenges we have in front of us now.

147
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:35,000
We want to think about this place that we're trying to go.

148
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:38,000
And we want to ask ourselves, who's been there before?

149
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:42,000
Do we have people in our network who know what those rooms look like?

150
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:45,000
The rooms that we don't have access to yet.

151
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:49,000
And if not, we want to identify this on this part of our page.

152
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:52,000
We want to outline and name the kind of community,

153
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:56,000
kind of support, the kind of expertise that we need that we're missing.

154
00:09:56,000 --> 00:10:01,000
Because the time to need your network is not the time to build your network.

155
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:06,000
And if you're gonna be getting across these gaps, you need to have those community members that you can call.

156
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:11,000
So you're gonna use this part of your page to name not just the people who can support you now,

157
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:17,000
but also to outline the kinds of folks, the kinds of expertise that you need to add to this network.

158
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:19,000
So that you can get building.

159
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:23,000
I have to tell you all, this is my favorite part of this single page plan.

160
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:27,000
If I had to just pick one section for you to work on, it would be this one.

161
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:29,000
But it doesn't matter, you can have all three.

162
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:30,000
So, sorry.

163
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:31,000
All right.

164
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:36,000
I told my friend that if you wanted to be president, all he needed was a single page.

165
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:39,000
And I've told you a little bit about the content, the research that I did,

166
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:42,000
the pattern that I found that makes that really important.

167
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:47,000
And there were three crucial things there, getting specific, setting those priorities,

168
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:50,000
and then thinking about community.

169
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:53,000
But it's not just those three things that I heard in the interview.

170
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:56,000
Again and again, as I would interview folks,

171
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:02,000
we would reflect on how just insanely busy the world is today,

172
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:08,000
how fast we're all moving at 100,000 miles an hour, trying to keep up with it.

173
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:16,000
And how when you're working on a goal, it is so helpful to have something in front of you that reminds you

174
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:20,000
despite all that noise of what you're working on.

175
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:22,000
That's part of the magic here.

176
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:27,000
It's not just the content of the single page, but it's also the single page itself.

177
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:32,000
In this really busy world, it is so important for you to be able to have something that's small enough

178
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:36,000
to keep in front of you to keep in your dorm room or in your office or in your back pocket

179
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:39,000
that reminds you what you're working on.

180
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:43,000
That keeps you focused on this really important goal.

181
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:46,000
It's also a very accessible tool.

182
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:49,000
At any point, you can have a new idea for something,

183
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:56,000
and all you need to do is just go grab a single page to get started to have that bias toward action.

184
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:00,000
I don't know if we ever needed more than a single page to plan our goals,

185
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:02,000
but we definitely don't these days.

186
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:06,000
It's also urgent.

187
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:11,000
I really need y'all to try this because selfishly,

188
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:14,000
I want to live in a world where your goals exist.

189
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:17,000
If you think about that thing that you want,

190
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:24,000
whether it's your art, your science, your leadership, your voice,

191
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:27,000
whatever it is that you want,

192
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:32,000
I think the world will be a better place when you make that happen.

193
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:37,000
I genuinely believe that our world will be a better place to live in

194
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:41,000
if more people are able to reach their goals,

195
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:46,000
are able to do those big things that I know that you have the potential to do.

196
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:51,000
I like to imagine that if you have a single page in front of you reminding you

197
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:55,000
of what those priorities are for your crucial actions,

198
00:12:55,000 --> 00:13:00,000
the people who can help support you that you're going to be more likely to make it happen.

199
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:03,000
I hope as you walk away from this that you know that I believe in you

200
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:06,000
and I believe in your potential, I hope you try this out.

201
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:09,000
Because honestly at this point,

202
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:14,000
my goal is that someday there's going to be some writer like me

203
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:17,000
who's writing about you.

204
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:18,000
Thanks.

205
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:20,000
Thank you.

